## Migration: `TimedExecutor` to .NET 8

### Key Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — removed entirely |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Never thrown — dead code |

`Thread.Abort()` was removed because it corrupts application state by unwinding the stack at arbitrary points, leaving locks held and objects half-initialized.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a cooperative cancellation timeout.
    /// The delegate must observe the <see cref="CancellationToken"/> to stop promptly.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block the caller, just like the original Thread.Join(timeout) did.
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }

        // Task.Result re-throws as AggregateException, matching original behavior.
        return task.Result;
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Async overload — preferred in new code.
    /// </summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Usage Comparison

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework) — work is forcibly killed
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SlowDatabaseCall(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER (.NET 8) — work must cooperate with cancellation
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct => SlowDatabaseCall(ct),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER (async) — preferred
var result = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(
    async ct => await SlowDatabaseCallAsync(ct),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Pitfalls

1. **Cooperative cancellation is not automatic.** The delegate *must* check `ct.IsCancellationRequested` or pass `ct` to APIs that accept it. If it doesn't, the work runs to completion even after timeout — unlike the old `Abort()` which killed it forcibly.

2. **Wrapping uncooperative code.** If you can't modify the work (e.g., third-party library with no `CancellationToken` support), the task will keep running after you stop waiting. There is no safe equivalent to `Abort()`:
   ```csharp
   // Fire-and-forget fallback for uncooperative work (last resort)
   public T ExecuteWithTimeoutUncooperative<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
   {
       var task = Task.Run(work);
       if (task.Wait(timeout))
           return task.Result;
       // Task keeps running in the background — resource leak by design
       throw new TimeoutException(
           $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
   }
   ```

3. **`Task.Result` wraps in `AggregateException`** — same as the original. If you want the inner exception, use `await` (async path) or call `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` instead.

4. **`WaitAsync()` (used in the async overload) requires .NET 6+.** You're on .NET 8, so this is fine.
